The Promenade at Castle Rock is a 160-acre development planned for the area bounded by
Interstate 25 (I-25), US Highway 85 (US 85), Meadows Parkway, and Castlegate Drive North. A
360-unit apartment complex is proposed in addition to 1,000,000 square feet (SF) of retail uses.
The site is planned to occupy undeveloped land surrounding the existing Outlets at Castle Rock
(Outlets) and adjoining retail and restaurant uses. Figure 1 illustrates the location of the site
relative to the surrounding roadway system.
Primary access to the site would be via extensions of the existing Factory Shops Boulevard and
Atrium Drive through the site, which would facilitate connection to the external roadway network,
including Meadows Parkway, US 85, Castlegate Drive North, Castlegate Drive West, and I-25.
Figure 2 depicts the current site plan concept and the individual blocks that comprise the
proposed development. Block 3B, in the northwest corner of the site, is the planned location of
the apartment complex. It is important to note that the site plan includes a vehicular connection
between Block 4B of the Promenade development and the Outlets.
The purpose of this analysis is to assess the traffic impacts related to the planned Promenade
at Castle Rock development and to identify any roadway or traffic control improvements needed
to accommodate the additional traffic. Study area roadways include both State Highways and
Town of Castle Rock roadways. The Town of Castle Rock Transportation Design Criteria
Manual (Castle Rock, 2012) and Colorado Department of Transportation (CDOT) State Highway
Access Code (SHAC) were used as references in preparing this analysis.
The base assumptions used for the analysis were coordinated with Town of Castle Rock and
CDOT staff before initiating the project. Two future planning horizons were evaluated:
 Short-Term Future. This scenario estimates conditions based on a near-term project
 Long-Term Future. A long-term (year 2035) scenario was chosen to provide a 20-year
planning horizon and to be consistent with the Denver Regional Council of Governments
For existing conditions and each future planning horizon, three peak travel periods were
evaluated to capture the transportation impacts of the proposed development:
 Weekday noon peak period (hereinafter referred to as noon peak hour)
 Weekday PM peak (hereinafter referred to as PM peak hour)
 Saturday afternoon peak (hereinafter referred to as Saturday peak hour)
Signal cycle length assumptions are provided as follows for all time horizons:

the form of the Outlets and adjoining retail and restaurant uses, which include the Lowe’s Home
Improvement Center along US 85. Existing residential development is located north and west of
The area contains an extensive existing roadway network as discussed in the following
Meadows Parkway/Founders Parkway is an arterial roadway that extends east-west
across the Castle Rock community and lies on the south edge of the Promenade site.
Named Meadows Parkway west of I-25 and Founders Parkway east of I-25, the arterial
interchanges with I-25 via a partial cloverleaf interchange. Meadows Parkway is also
designated US 85 between I-25 and Santa Fe Drive. Founders Parkway is also
designated as State Highway 86. The basic number of lanes along both Meadows and
Founders Parkways is four lanes, and the roadway widens to provide six travel lanes
Adjacent to the site, Meadows Parkway has a posted speed of 45 miles per hour (mph).
The intersections of Meadows Parkway with Santa Fe Drive, Factory Shops Boulevard,
and the I-25 interchange ramp terminal intersections are signalized. Meadows Parkway
is categorized as a NR-A (Non-Rural Arterial) for CDOT access purposes.
 Interstate 25 (I-25): I-25 runs along the eastern edge of the site. The segment of I-25
along the Promenade property is an eight-lane interstate freeway with a posted speed of
75 mph. The posted speed limit is reduced to 65 mph approximately 0.75 miles north of
the existing Meadows/Founders interchange. A new I-25 interchange with North
Meadows Drive/Castlegate Drive North is currently under construction.
 Santa Fe Drive (US 85): Santa Fe Drive is a State Highway (85B) that extends north-
south across much of Colorado. In the vicinity of the site, it is a four-lane arterial that is
posted at 55 mph. The speed limit reduces to 45 mph south of New Beale Street. It is
 Castlegate Drive West: Castlegate Drive West is a two-lane collector roadway that
serves as the northern extension of Factory Shops Boulevard. It is posted at 35 mph.
 Castlegate Drive North: Castlegate Drive North is a two-lane collector roadway that
serves to connect Castlegate Drive West to Santa Fe Drive. It is posted at 35 mph.
 Factory Shops Boulevard/Castlegate Drive West: Factory Shops Boulevard currently
provides access from the Outlets to Meadows Parkway. It is planned to be extended
northwest through the site to serve as a continuous link from Meadows Parkway to
Castlegate Drive North parallel to Santa Fe Drive. Factory Shops Boulevard is four lanes
wide between Meadows Parkway and New Beale Street, then narrows to two lanes
north of New Beale Street. Factory Shops Boulevard is posted at 25 mph.
 North Castleton Drive: North Castleton Drive aligns with Factory Shops Boulevard and
extends south from Meadows Parkway. The street provides access to the developed
area southeast of Meadows Parkway. The street has two through lanes in the southeast-
bound direction and one through lane in the northwest-bound direction, plus left-turn
lanes at intersections. The posted speed limit is 30 mph.
 Atrium Drive: Atrium Drive currently extends east from Santa Fe Drive into the site,
providing a connection between Factory Shops Boulevard and Castlegate Drive West on
a semicircular alignment. In the future, Atrium Drive is anticipated to extend across the
site and connect with the new I-25/North Meadows Drive-Castlegate Drive North
interchange. The Atrium Drive/Santa Fe Drive intersection is signalized.

Existing traffic operations were analyzed at the study area intersections based on procedures
documented in the Highway Capacity Manual (Transportation Research Board, 2010). Level of
Service (LOS) is a qualitative measure of traffic operational conditions, based on roadway
capacity and motorist delay. LOS ranges from A to F, with LOS A representing the best possible
operating conditions and LOS F representing over-capacity, or congested conditions. For
unsignalized intersections, LOS is calculated for movements that must yield right-of-way (ROW)
to other traffic movements and is typically reported for the movement or approach with the
highest delay. For signalized traffic control, LOS represents an average of the delays for all
The Town of Castle Rock Transportation Design Criteria Manual states that the minimum
acceptable LOS for all intersections in the Town shall be LOS D or better, and LOS E or better
As indicated on Figures 5 and 6, and summarized in Table 1, the study area signalized
intersections currently operate within acceptable limits, at LOS D or better during peak times,
with the exception of the Meadows Parkway/Santa Fe Drive intersection, which operates at
LOS E during the PM peak hour. The westbound left-turn movement from at the Santa Fe
Drive/Castlegate Drive North intersection also operates at LOS F during the weekday PM peak
hour. Appendix B contains SYNCHRO LOS analysis worksheets for the existing conditions.

As depicted on Figure 2, the current site plan concept includes approximately 1,000,000 SF of
retail space and a 360-unit apartment complex to be located within Block 3B in the northwest
corner of the site. Site trip generation estimates were developed for weekday and Saturday daily
traffic and each of the three peak hours to be analyzed. Because of the large size of the
proposed development, it is anticipated that a significant number of internal vehicle-trips will
occur between the various blocks of development. Town of Castle Rock staff requested that
these trips be estimated and assigned to the network as a unique component of site traffic, in
Recognizing the unique site requirements, the methodology for calculating site external and
internal trip generation was developed in collaboration with CDOT and Town of Castle Rock
representatives. Information contained in Trip Generation, 9
Transportation Engineers (ITE) was used to develop estimates of the vehicle-trips expected to
be generated from the site. Shopping Center (ITE Land Use Code [LUC]: 820) was found to be
the most compatible land use type for the retail areas of the site. Apartments (ITE LUC: 220)
was selected for the planned apartment units. The average Shopping Center rate was selected,
rather than the fitted regression equation. For the Promenade development, applying the
average rate to a shopping center 1,000,000 SF in size yields an estimated total number of
vehicle-trips approximately 20 to 40 percent higher than the estimates derived using the fitted
regression equation. The average rate provides a conservatively high site trip generation
estimate; from which internal trip capture reductions and pass-by adjustments were applied.
With the internal capture reductions and pass-by adjustments applied to the average rate, the
resultant external trip generation closely corresponds to the trip generation calculated using the
The methodology used appears to adequately account for the external/internal trip generation
characteristics of the site. The calculation of internal trips followed the methodology for multi-use
developments described in Trip Generation Handbook, 2
Handbook says internal capture rates are not applicable for shopping centers, given the overall
area of the site and variety of retail land uses it is planned to contain (restaurants, large box
retail, specialty retail, etc.), it was appropriate to apply internal capture rates to the average
This brings the overall site trip generation closely in line to what it would be if the fitted
regression equation had been selected and no internal capture rates applied.
Based on the characteristics of the site development and surrounding roadway network, it was
determined that total site vehicle trip generation would include three components: new external,
internal, and pass-by trips. Diverted linked trips were initially considered as a potential additional
component due to the potential for drivers to visit the site via I-25 and US 85; however, it is not
likely the diverted linked trips would result in a significant shift in travel patterns. For this reason,
no calculation was performed for diverted linked trips.
Trip Generation provides rates for PM and Saturday peak hours, but no comparable information
Therefore, a noon peak hour trip generation rate was derived for the retail uses using
information contained in Trip Generation that relates noon peak hour retail traffic to other hours
of the day. Based on this information, the noon peak hour rate was found to be slightly higher
(less than 1 percent) than that of the PM peak hour. For the Apartments, it was assumed that
the noon peak hour rate would be equal to half the rate for the PM peak hour.
The site can be considered a mixed-use development because it contains a variety of retail
uses, together with the apartments. The Trip Generation Handbook, 2
internal capture rates for trips anticipated to be made between the on-site retail uses, in addition
to trips made between the retail and residential uses. Available information indicates that during
the noon peak hour, about 30 percent of trips between retail uses are made internal to the site
and 20 percent during the PM peak hour. It was assumed that during the Saturday peak hour,
30 percent of trips between retail uses would be internal to the site, given that visitors likely
have more time available to shop and would be inclined to make multiple stops to various
establishments within the site. The internal trips were assigned from block-to-block within the
The total site trip generation was also adjusted to account for vehicle-trips that would occur
between the proposed Promenade retail uses and the existing Outlets and residential uses
along Castlegate Drive West. The capture rate between the existing uses and the proposed
development was developed using the internal capture worksheets contained in the Trip
Edition, 2004, then was halved to be conservative, resulting in an
estimated approximate 5 percent of site trips to and from the existing immediately adjacent
development. The 360-unit apartment complex proposed within the Promenade development
was not included in this calculation.
The heavy presence of retail uses and the location of the site relative to the surrounding street
system mean that pass-by trips, defined as trips attracted to the site while already driving past
on their way to another destination outside the development, are possible. For this reason,
based on information contained in Trip Generation Handbook, 2
adjustment was applied to the external retail trip generation estimates for pass-by trips during
the noon and Saturday peak hours, and a 20 percent adjustment for pass-by trips was applied
during the PM peak hour. The pass-by adjustments selected correspond closely to the pass-by
rates calculated using information contained in Figures 5.5 and 5.7 of Trip Generation
Pass-by trip adjustments do not apply to the proposed apartments.
The new external trips are found by taking the total trip generation for the site and subtracting
the adjustments made for internal trips and pass-by trips.

page.text: The global distribution of site trips to the surrounding network was developed based on the
planned street network, previous studies conducted in the area, and coordination with Town of
Castle Rock and CDOT staff. The global directional distribution percentages developed apply to
both the short- and long-range analyses and all blocks within the development. External site trip
routing was developed on a block-by-block basis, each block with a customized set of paths
used to travel to and from the site. More direct paths from a given block to an external location
were assigned a higher percentage of traffic attributable to that block’s development. For
example, vehicle-trips associated with Blocks 7 and 8 (at the southern portion of the project site)
were more likely to use the I-25/Founders-Meadows Parkway interchange to access I-25 than
areas within the site located farther north, such as Blocks 1 and 2.
The global directional distribution percentages are described below and are illustrated on
Figure 7, which also depicts the new external trip splits of site vehicle-trips oriented to/from
northbound and southbound I-25 and Founders Parkway assigned to each of the two I-25

It should be noted that although the trips between the various proposed blocks of development
are described as being internal to the site, these trips would be made using Town of Castle
Rock public streets, including Atrium Drive, Castlegate Drive North, Castlegate Drive West,
Factory Shops Boulevard, and New Beale Street. The internal trips were assigned between
blocks based on the relative magnitude of development within each block and the shortest or
most direct travel paths between blocks/land uses.
A separate distribution was developed to assign the pass-by trips. Pass-by trips were assumed
to occur from three streets adjacent to the site: Santa Fe Drive (US 85), Castlegate Drive North,
and Meadows Parkway (between I-25 and Santa Fe Drive). The pass-by distribution was based,
in part, on the projected future traffic volumes on each of these streets, as well as the proximity
of the street to the proposed retail portions of the development. The pass-by distribution differs
for the three analysis time periods based primarily on the directionality of the through traffic
volumes on each of the three adjacent streets. Pass-by trips were assigned to these roadways
based on the following overall percentages:
 40 percent to/from Santa Fe Drive via Atrium Drive and New Beale Street
 40 percent to/from Castlegate Drive North via Atrium Drive
 20 percent to/from Meadows Parkway via Factory Shops Boulevard/N. Castleton Drive
For the noon and Saturday peak hours, the following directional splits were applied to the pass-
by trips assigned to each roadway:
 Santa Fe Drive (50 percent from the north and 50 percent from the south)
 Castlegate Drive North (50 percent from the north/east and 50 percent from the west)
 Meadows Parkway (50 percent from the east and 50 percent from the west)
During the PM peak hour, the following directional splits were applied to the overall pass-by trip
 Santa Fe Drive (63 percent from the north and 37 percent from the south)
 Castlegate Drive North (75 percent from the north/east and 25 percent from the west)
 Meadows Parkway (75 percent from the east and 25 percent from the west)

Background traffic is the component of traffic volumes on the local street network that is
unrelated to the proposed development. Background conditions were analyzed to establish a
By the Year 2017, it is anticipated that the I-25/North Meadows Drive-Castlegate Drive North
interchange will be complete, as it is currently under construction, and Castlegate Drive North
will become a continuous roadway connection from the new interchange to Santa Fe Drive.
West of Santa Fe Drive, Castlegate Drive North will become North Meadows Parkway and
extend west from Santa Fe Drive across Plum Creek to provide access to development. The
North Meadows Drive/Santa Fe Drive intersection will be reconstructed as a Single-Point Urban
Interchange (SPUI), with North Meadows Drive crossing above Santa Fe Drive.
CDOT is currently making improvements to the I-25/Founders-Meadows Parkway interchange
that will adjust lane geometry. The following changes are planned:
 Adjust the southbound ramp terminal intersection to provide three eastbound through
lanes instead of two. Reconfigure the southbound off-ramp approach to provide triple
left-turn lanes onto eastbound Meadows Parkway.
 Widen the loop ramp to northbound I-25 to provide two lanes exiting from Meadows
Parkway. At the northbound loop ramp, there will be two eastbound through lanes, one
shared through/right-turn lane and one exclusive right-turn lane.
 Reconfigure the northbound ramp terminal to provide for signalized dual northbound
right-turn lanes and three eastbound through lanes. These planned roadway network
changes are reflected in the analysis of Year 2017 background traffic conditions.
Background traffic forecasts for the Year 2017 scenario were developed using the following
1. Develop a Year 2010 (base year) model run using the DRCOG regional travel demand
model with the I-25/North Meadows Drive-Castlegate Drive North interchange included
in the roadway network, along with the extension of North Meadows Drive west from
Santa Fe Drive. Quantify differences between the model run and the base 2010 network
to understand traffic shifts that will occur upon completion of the interchange and North
2. Use the base year model to manually adjust the Year 2014 traffic counts at the existing
intersections to reflect a scenario with the interchange and extension in place. Use the
traffic forecasts included in the North Meadows Extension to US 85 and I-25 Interstate
Access Request (IAR) as a reference in making adjustments, as the IAR undertook a
similar exercise of adjusting interchange no-build volumes to reflect a build condition for
the I-25/North Meadows Drive-Castlegate Drive North interchange.
3. Increase traffic volumes at a rate of one percent per year to account for general growth
to the Year 2017, and add in traffic volumes generated by the proposed fast casual
restaurant and coffee shop to be constructed by 2017, based on information included in
the supporting Traffic Impact Study, Starbucks/Qdoba at Castle Rock Factory Shops
Figures 10 and 11 depict the resulting background traffic forecasts. As shown, the presence of
the I-25/North Meadows Drive-Castlegate Drive North interchange is expected to reduce traffic
volumes along Meadows Parkway and the I-25/Founders-Meadows Parkway interchange by
providing a new means of accessing areas west of I-25.

As shown, LOS is expected to improve at the Meadows Parkway intersections with Santa Fe
Drive, Factory Shops Boulevard, and I-25 Northbound and Southbound Ramps. LOS is also
expected to improve at the intersection of Factory Shops Boulevard with New Memphis Court.
The greatest contributing factor to the LOS improvements is the projected traffic diversion to

interchange and roadway extension. In the case of the PM peak hour, a few minor adjustments

at Factory Shops Boulevard/New Memphis was adjusted to match the Factory Shops
Boulevard/Meadows Parkway cycle length in 2017, while it currently operates at ½ the cycle
length of Factory Shops Boulevard/Meadows Parkway.

 Castlegate Drive North/Castlegate Drive West: Upon completion of the I-25/North
Meadows Drive-Castlegate Drive North interchange and North Meadows Drive

 Atrium Drive Intersections: Three full-movement intersections are proposed along

threshold traffic volume ranges for roundabout consideration (Roundabouts, an

page.text: As shown in the tables, the majority of locations show daily and/or PM peak hour traffic
forecasts that are of a similar magnitude in comparison with the IAR forecasts. Some locations
show differences. For example, Atrium Drive south of Castlegate Drive North was forecasted in
the IAR to carry 10,000 vpd and 2,230 vph in the PM peak hour. The TIA forecasts higher daily
traffic levels and lower peak hour forecasts. The following points are provided as reasons why
 Different travel demand model versions: The IAR forecasts were developed using the
Year 2030 regional travel demand model and associated land use and roadway network
assumptions, while the TIA forecasts were based on the Year 2035 travel demand
model. In addition to modeling a different forecast year, the TIA incorporated a number
of additional refinements to the base travel demand model, including land use and
roadway classification adjustments based on the latest forecasting efforts of Town Staff.
 Different site land use assumptions: The IAR forecast traffic volumes include vehicle-
trips generated by potential development of some portion of the Promenade area based
on previous, preliminary development concepts. The Promenade TIA forecasts were
developed using the current site plan land uses, which differ from the previous
Atrium Drive Intersections: Three full-movement intersections are proposed along Atrium
Drive. Based on forecasted total traffic volumes, unsignalized (STOP sign) control at each
intersection is anticipated to be inadequate to provide acceptable intersection LOS. The project
team evaluated projected total traffic levels at each intersection in light of threshold traffic
volume ranges for roundabout consideration and signalization warrants. It was found that each
of the four intersections could be considered for either signalization or installation of a
roundabout. However, as described in the Section IV.B of this report, roundabouts are not
preferable due to physical concerns. Nevertheless, based on a meeting with Town of Castle
Rock staff and the developer, a roundabout appears to be the Town’s preferred option for
Intersection #13b. For this reason, this intersection was analyzed only as a roundabout in this
report. Intersection #15 was analyzed as both a roundabout and a traffic signal and both were
shown to operate acceptably. Final determination of the intersection traffic control will need to
be further evaluated as design of the roundabout is refined and its impacts to the site layout are
better understood. In general, the same traffic control assumed for the Year 2017 total scenario
is carried forward into the 2035 analysis.

acceptable LOS with the addition of site traffic to Year 2035 background traffic forecasts.
